Professional Studies Implements Digital Badging System to Recognize Completion of Noncredit Certificates                             School is One of the First Institutions of Higher Learning in the Region to Employ Digital Credentialing           NEW YORK, October 21, 2013 —In today's tumultuous job market, earning a noncredit certificate provides motivated individuals with the opportunity to acquire additional skills and knowledge that enable them to launch, to advance, or to change their careers.   The NYU School of Continuing and Professional Studies (NYU-SCPS) offers over 100 professionally oriented, noncredit certificates in a broad range of fields—from real estate to digital journalism, fundraising to social media. Earning a noncredit credential demonstrates—to prospective employers, current employers, and colleagues—that a job candidate or a current employee has demonstrated a deep commitment to remaining at the cutting edge of his or her area of expertise.   With the explosion of social media and the distribution of digital documents, NYU-SCPS realized the potential and the value of providing a digital badge as recognition of completion of a noncredit certificate that can be displayed within an individual's social media profile or embedded into his or her digital résumé. Working with Basno, a company that provides the technology to implement the program, NYU-SCPS recently launched a digital badging system for its noncredit certificate programs. After earning a certificate, completers simply claim their badge through the School's website. They can then spread the word of their achievements virally.   "Thousands of individuals have earned noncredit certificates through NYU-SCPS," said Dean Dennis Di Lorenzo."The new digital badging system provides them with the ability to promote their accomplishments in a high-tech environment, and to gain a competitive edge."   Each digital badge is hot-linked to a certificate description. Viewers, including prospective employers, can click on the badge to access the general content of the certificate program as well as the level of expertise earned. In the near future, the School plans to implement an additional badging program for its individual noncredit courses. For more information, visit: scps.nyu.edu/ce/badges .            About the NYU School of Continuing and Professional Studies            Established in 1934, NYU-SCPS ( scps.nyu.edu ) is one of NYU’s several degree-granting schools and colleges, each with a unique academic profile. The reputation of NYU-SCPS arises from its place as the NYU home for study and applied research related to key knowledge-based industries where the New York region leads globally. This is manifest in the School’s diverse graduate, undergraduate, and noncredit programs in fields such as Real Estate, Real Estate Development, and Construction Management; Hospitality, Tourism, and Sports Management; Global Affairs; Fundraising and Grantmaking; Publishing; Professional Writing; Human Resource Management and Development, Marketing, Public Relations and Corporate Communication, Management and Systems, Advanced Digital Applications, Graphic Communications Management and Technology, Project Management, and Accounting, Finance, and Law; Liberal and Allied Arts; Foreign Languages, Translation, and Interpreting; Applied Politics; and Health Information Management.    More than 100 distinguished full-time faculty members collaborate with an exceptional cadre of practitioner/adjunct faculty and lecturers to create vibrant professional and academic networks that annually attract nearly 5,000 degree-seeking students from around the globe. In addition, the School fulfills the recurrent continuing higher education needs of local and professional communities, as evidenced by close to 48,000 annual noncredit enrollments in individual courses, specialized certificate programs, workshops, and seminars. The School’s community is enriched by more than 27,000 degree-holding alumni worldwide, many of whom serve as mentors, guest speakers, and advisory board members. For more information, visit: scps.nyu.edu .
